SIMPLE: hydrotropism
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hydrotropism
<hw>Hy*drot"ro*pism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A tendency towards moisture.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>In a broader sense, any curvature
or turning induced in certain growing plant organs under the influence
of moisture.</def></p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ When the movement is toward the moisture, as is the case
in most roots, the phenomenon is called <stype>positive
hydrotropism</stype>; when away from the moisture, as in the case of
hyphae of certain fungi, <stype>negative
hydrotropism</stype>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hydrous</ent>⟦br⟧
